WEBVTT

1
00:00:29.270 --> 00:00:31.570
Hey. howdy there. Mr. Lee.

2
00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:34.030
What is this? Filipino New Year's?

3
00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:36.030
No. Why you say that?

4
00:00:36.200 --> 00:00:37.870
Because you're cooking up a feast.

5
00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:40.660
l can smell it all the way
from the interstate.

6
00:00:40.830 --> 00:00:43.290
What is that? Barbecue?

7
00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:46.250
Oh. yeah. But it not coming from here.

8
00:00:46.790 --> 00:00:48.420
What is that noise?

9
00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:55.970
Daddy!

10
00:01:00.970 --> 00:01:03.180
-Daddy!
-Daddy!

11
00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:22.800
What is your take on this. Jerry?

12
00:04:22.970 --> 00:04:25.680
The people are gonna love it.
Mr. President.

13
00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:30.390
Our only conflict is whether we ambush
the 6:00 news or hold out for prime time.

14
00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:32.930
Screw the press.
This is a need-to-know situation.

15
00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:34.640
We should make it top secret...

16
00:04:34.810 --> 00:04:36.980
...and move in right away
with DEFCON 4.

17
00:04:37.150 --> 00:04:39.110
Mr. President. we cannot sit on this.

18
00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:44.360
General Casey. do you have an opinion?

19
00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:47.280
Well. sir. do we know they're hostile?

20
00:04:47.450 --> 00:04:49.870
What do you mean.
"do we know they're hostile?"

21
00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:52.740
They have our planet surrounded
with thousands of warships.

22
00:04:52.910 --> 00:04:54.450
Do we know they're warships?

23
00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:01.130
Professor. what do we know about them?

24
00:05:02.670 --> 00:05:05.090
We know they're extremely advanced
technologically...

25
00:05:05.260 --> 00:05:08.300
...which suggests. very rightfully so.
that they're peaceful.

26
00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:13.220
An advanced civilization is.
by definition. not barbaric.

27
00:05:13.390 --> 00:05:16.520
Mr. President. this is a great day.

28
00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:20.480
l and all my colleagues
are extremely excited.

29
00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:23.030
Good.

30
00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:26.400
Extraterrestrial life.

31
00:05:27.070 --> 00:05:28.570
You're right. Jerry.

32
00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:31.070
The people are gonna love it.

33
00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:33.700
This is a momentous occasion.

34
00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:37.290
-Mr. President. we have to act--
We'll go all media on this.

35
00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:42.210
l'll wear my blue Cerruti suit.
And. Jerry. l'll need a good speech.

36
00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:43.460
Statesman-like...

37
00:05:44.050 --> 00:05:47.920
...historical and yet warm and neighborly.

38
00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:51.890
Abraham Lincoln meets Leave It to Beaver.
You know the sort of thing. Heh.

39
00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:53.180
Yes. sir.

40
00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:55.100
Are they too old-fashioned?
Yes.

41
00:05:55.270 --> 00:05:56.730
No. l don't think so.

42
00:05:56.890 --> 00:06:00.350
This has got the colors. but no.
l don't think so.

43
00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:02.060
-Not vivid enough.
-Mm-hm. Mm-hm.

44
00:06:02.230 --> 00:06:04.860
-Nancy had this in the library. didn't she?
-Yes. indeed.

45
00:06:05.030 --> 00:06:06.150
l don't think so.

46
00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:09.950
l thought perhaps the watered silk.
And this week it's on sale.

47
00:06:10.110 --> 00:06:12.740
l hardly think l need worry about that.

48
00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:15.580
My husband is the leader
of the free world.

49
00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:18.870
What do you think. Taffy?

50
00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:22.630
Why don't you leave the Roosevelt Room
the way the Roosevelts wanted it?

51
00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:27.960
Because Eleanor Roosevelt
was too fond of chintz. That's why.

52
00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:30.430
Mother. this isn't your house.

53
00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:33.680
Taffy. if you're going to be a pest.
l'm going to ignore you.

54
00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:36.600
-Mrs. Dale?
-Yes?

55
00:06:57.500 --> 00:07:01.420
-l saw you fight Sonny Liston in '69.
-Really?

56
00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:03.830
-You mean. you were a nun back then?
-Oh. yes.

57
00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.050
We've always been fight fans.
haven't we. sisters?

58
00:07:07.210 --> 00:07:09.090
Byron Williams. telephone.

59
00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:11.220
-Byron Williams....
-That's me. l gotta go.

60
00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:13.930
You ladies have a nice time. all right?
Thank you.

61
00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:19.390
-Yeah?
-Byron?

62
00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:20.600
Oh. Louise.

63
00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:23.150
l'm sorry l have to call you at work.

64
00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:27.940
The boys haven't been home in two nights
and l don't know what to do.

65
00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:30.190
Listen. you're doing the best you can.

66
00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:32.150
They're just at that age.

67
00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:37.280
Louise. the casino manager's
giving me the evil eye. l've gotta go.

68
00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:39.660
l'll call you later. okay?

69
00:07:40.620 --> 00:07:43.620
Hey. are you still cool on me
coming to Washington?

70
00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:45.460
Sure. Of course l am.

71
00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:49.210
You take care. okay? Bye.

72
00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:04.100
Ahh....

73
00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:06.230
Do you have to drink in front of me?

74
00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:08.520
You're an adult. Just cope.

75
00:08:08.690 --> 00:08:11.820
lt doesn't help me
that all we ever do is sit around in bars.

76
00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:14.110
Hey. This is work. baby. okay?

77
00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:17.700
l'm checking the decor.
the lighting. the traffic flow.

78
00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:21.080
lf l'd known you'd turn into a crook.
l never would have married you.

79
00:08:21.250 --> 00:08:22.790
l'm not a crook.

80
00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:25.330
l'm ambitious. There's a difference.

81
00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:28.080
And if you think you can make
a nickel in this town...

82
00:08:28.250 --> 00:08:32.130
...without knowing how to dally
around a few curves. well...

83
00:08:32.300 --> 00:08:34.930
...you don't know doodlysquat
about the gaming industry.

84
00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:36.300
Oh. Art.

85
00:08:36.470 --> 00:08:40.430
Galaxy's gonna be
the best hotel in Vegas.

86
00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:43.020
The best. l promise.

87
00:08:43.180 --> 00:08:45.980
Don't you realize what you're doing?
Destroying the Earth.

88
00:08:46.150 --> 00:08:49.020
All this greed. This money system.

89
00:08:49.190 --> 00:08:50.900
You're destroying everything.

90
00:08:51.070 --> 00:08:53.990
Okay. okay. Barbara. Okay.

91
00:08:54.360 --> 00:08:56.820
Keep your voice down.

92
00:08:57.370 --> 00:08:59.660
l got friends here.

93
00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:03.250
Sugar. Hit me one more time.

94
00:09:03.410 --> 00:09:06.210
-Stop flirting with the waitress.
-Oh. God. Here.

95
00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:09.580
Go on over to the roulette...

96
00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:12.800
...play our anniversary...

97
00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:15.090
...and stay off of black.

98
00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:19.390
Thanks. honey.

99
00:09:26.230 --> 00:09:27.480
Yeah?

100
00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:30.650
Make it quick.
We go out live in 10 minutes.

101
00:09:31.270 --> 00:09:34.820
What? The actual president?
What do you mean. "cutting in"?

102
00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.990
Budget negotiations may be dead
in the water after this week.

103
00:09:42.740 --> 00:09:44.660
Hair looks good.

104
00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:46.370
l like the hair.

105
00:09:46.540 --> 00:09:48.290
--quote. "factually challenged."
Griffin says....

106
00:09:49.670 --> 00:09:51.330
Yeah. Stone. Speak.

107
00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:52.960
Jason. hi. it's me.

108
00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:55.920
You wearing a bra?

109
00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:59.760
Listen. this is big. President Dale
is cutting into my show today.

110
00:10:01.350 --> 00:10:04.350
That's absurd. Why would he stoop
to being on Today in Fashion?

111
00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:05.850
He's interrupting everybody.

112
00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:09.390
l don't know. it's some sort of
emergency announcement or something.

113
00:10:09.560 --> 00:10:11.980
This doesn't make sense.
He should be talking to us.

114
00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:15.820
White House is coming out live.

115
00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:19.150
Good evening. my fellow Americans.

116
00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:23.030
l apologize for interrupting
your regular programs...

117
00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:26.330
...but l have a very important
announcement to make.

118
00:10:27.040 --> 00:10:29.870
Many important things have happened
to me in my life:

119
00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:32.670
My graduation from Princeton...

120
00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:36.500
...the day that Marsha said
she would be my wife...

121
00:10:36.670 --> 00:10:38.760
...the birth of our daughter. Taffy.

122
00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:39.970
Thanks. Dad.

123
00:10:40.550 --> 00:10:42.720
And the news that I have heard today...

124
00:10:42.890 --> 00:10:45.010
-...ranks right up there.
-Thank you.

125
00:10:45.770 --> 00:10:48.100
A powerful memory is in the making.

126
00:10:48.270 --> 00:10:49.890
Not just for me...

127
00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:52.060
...but for all mankind.

128
00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:57.940
Today. an extraordinary discovery
was made by the Hubble telescope.

129
00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:02.700
The data from the Hubble was decoded...

130
00:11:02.870 --> 00:11:04.910
...then analyzed
by the most powerful computers at MlT.

131
00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:10.290
The images are undeniable.

132
00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:14.290
We are entering the dawn of a new era.

133
00:11:15.250 --> 00:11:18.920
Frame enlargements
provide an astonishing sight.

134
00:11:19.590 --> 00:11:24.090
A fleet of vehicles.
which can best be described as...

135
00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:25.640
...flying saucers.

136
00:11:25.810 --> 00:11:29.470
Come on. Come on.
Papa needs a new pair of shoes.

137
00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:31.520
Hey!

138
00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:34.150
Hey. am l the only one
shooting craps here?

139
00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:37.730
--we will have
the opportunity to meet with them.

140
00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:41.070
l feel this is the perfect summation
to the 20th century....

141
00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:43.280
Martians.

142
00:11:43.450 --> 00:11:44.910
This is great.

143
00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:48.660
Please come to Earth. Please.

144
00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:50.580
We need you.

145
00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:57.130
l got people coming in.

146
00:11:57.290 --> 00:12:00.300
Everybody wants to be a part of this.

147
00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:03.340
Galaxy's gonna be world-class.

148
00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:05.140
And soon...

149
00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:08.350
...we will become one solar system.

150
00:12:08.890 --> 00:12:10.680
What the hell is he talking about?

151
00:12:10.850 --> 00:12:14.310
These flying saucers
have come from the planet Mars...

152
00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:17.690
-...and at their current course and speed....
-Oh. Hey.

153
00:12:17.860 --> 00:12:23.450
Listen. Hoss. l've been thinking about
Martians when there wasn't no Martians.

154
00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:28.320
lt is profoundly moving
to know there is intelligent life out there.

155
00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:29.780
Glad they got it somewhere.

156
00:12:29.950 --> 00:12:34.330
And our world will never feel
quite the same again.

157
00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:37.290
Good night...

158
00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:39.840
...and God bless you all.

159
00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:51.930
This...

160
00:12:52.310 --> 00:12:53.520
...is intense.

161
00:12:56.810 --> 00:12:58.690
Shut up. Poppy. Shut up.

162
00:12:59.690 --> 00:13:01.520
Shut up.

163
00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:03.690
Jason Stone.

164
00:13:06.030 --> 00:13:07.700
lt's for you.

165
00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:11.410
Poppy. honey. No. sweetie.

166
00:13:13.450 --> 00:13:17.210
That's right. Shh. Good girl. Yeah?

167
00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:21.500
Yeah. Well. l could be there at...

168
00:13:21.670 --> 00:13:23.460
...l don't know. 11.

169
00:13:24.420 --> 00:13:26.590
Okay. bye-bye.

170
00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:38.060
Yes?

171
00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:42.150
Oh. they want me to go interview
that professor from the White House.

172
00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:44.900
Kessler?

173
00:13:45.950 --> 00:13:48.240
-Donald Kessler?
-Yeah. l think that was his name.

174
00:13:48.410 --> 00:13:51.070
You know. the science guy.

175
00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:53.450
This is nuts. this is....

176
00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:55.120
We should have got that guy.

177
00:13:56.080 --> 00:13:59.040
Well. l can't help it
if your people are too slow.

178
00:13:59.210 --> 00:14:00.250
Right. Poppy?

179
00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:27.280
-Finished!
-One minute. 57 seconds.

180
00:14:27.610 --> 00:14:30.950
-Ha-ha! Didn't l tell you under two minutes?
-You did.

181
00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:33.870
You did. l'm so proud of you.

182
00:14:34.030 --> 00:14:36.700
-Hey. Ma. you want a doughnut?
-How old are they?

183
00:14:36.870 --> 00:14:38.000
Fresh-baked Monday.

184
00:14:38.580 --> 00:14:41.460
Richie. that's six days ago.

185
00:14:41.630 --> 00:14:42.920
Okay. give me a couple.

186
00:14:46.630 --> 00:14:49.090
Hey. this Martian thing
is pretty awesome. huh?

187
00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:52.970
Did any one of you traitors
see my Muffy?

188
00:14:53.140 --> 00:14:54.850
Your brother's gonna volunteer.

189
00:14:55.010 --> 00:14:57.140
As soon as l get back to the base.

190
00:14:57.310 --> 00:15:00.100
-Volunteer for what. Billy Glenn?
-Martian detail.

191
00:15:00.270 --> 00:15:01.940
-Uh-huh.
-Cool.

192
00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:04.110
lf any of them Martians
come around here...

193
00:15:04.270 --> 00:15:06.400
...l'm gonna kick their butts.
Heh-heh-heh.

194
00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:19.660
Jump!

195
00:15:28.710 --> 00:15:31.050
Excuse me. folks.
but we gotta make an unscheduled stop.

196
00:15:34.510 --> 00:15:36.350
lt's Mama.

197
00:15:36.510 --> 00:15:39.680
What are you doing here? Huh?
lf you ain't home. why ain't you in class?

198
00:15:39.850 --> 00:15:42.390
-Mama. class was canceled.
-Class was not canceled.

199
00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:44.150
-Come here. Come here.
-For what?

200
00:15:44.310 --> 00:15:46.060
l'm not gonna hurt you.
Now. come here.

201
00:15:46.230 --> 00:15:48.020
Let go of him.

202
00:15:48.690 --> 00:15:51.070
Okay. Now. just come here.

203
00:15:51.650 --> 00:15:53.400
Come here.

204
00:15:54.070 --> 00:15:55.530
Think it's smart to cut school?

205
00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:58.200
-What are you doing?
-Do you? Do you? Huh? Huh?

206
00:15:58.370 --> 00:15:59.660
-No.
-"No. Mama." lt's dumb.

207
00:15:59.830 --> 00:16:01.830
-You're gonna flunk and go to jail.
No.

208
00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.420
Get your butt on the bus.
Get on that bus. boy.

209
00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:07.710
l'll be tripping all over you.
Get back there.

210
00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:10.550
-l don't want to hear another word.
l hate school.

211
00:16:10.710 --> 00:16:12.630
l heard that.

212
00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:36.910
Hi.
-Hi there.

213
00:16:37.070 --> 00:16:40.030
Want a date?
How about it?

214
00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:41.830
A date?

215
00:16:43.790 --> 00:16:44.830
Sounds good.

216
00:16:47.460 --> 00:16:49.000
The stress at work is...

217
00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:51.550
...unbelievable.

218
00:16:56.430 --> 00:16:58.260
Mr. Bava. can l speak to you in private?

219
00:16:58.430 --> 00:17:01.390
No. l gotta watch the floor.
What do you want. Byron?

220
00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:05.020
-l'm supporting my family back East.
-l thought you were divorced.

221
00:17:05.600 --> 00:17:08.940
Well. l am.
but l still have to take care of them.

222
00:17:09.110 --> 00:17:11.980
Anyway. look. Things have been
a little lean around here...

223
00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:14.360
...and l was wondering
if l could get a raise?

224
00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:17.450
-Out of the question.
-Mr. Bava. l'm an asset to this hotel.

225
00:17:17.610 --> 00:17:20.580
-l mean. they like me around here.
-Byron. you're a nice guy.

226
00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:24.700
But l can get Leon Spinks or Buster Douglas
for the same money. maybe less.

227
00:17:25.250 --> 00:17:28.420
You better get moving.
You're on in five minutes.

228
00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:40.390
This show's gonna get
a hell of a rating.

229
00:17:40.600 --> 00:17:41.680
lt's all yours. lan.

230
00:17:41.850 --> 00:17:44.770
--language you choose to employ.
and in certain circumstances...

231
00:17:44.930 --> 00:17:47.640
...the proposition that two and two
equals five...

232
00:17:47.810 --> 00:17:49.650
...is entirely legitimate.

233
00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:52.610
Call me Nathalie.

234
00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:55.990
And you. do please call me Donald.

235
00:17:57.490 --> 00:17:59.570
l've always admired your show.

236
00:18:01.450 --> 00:18:03.870
Really? You like my work?

237
00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:06.160
Yes. Very much.

238
00:18:06.330 --> 00:18:08.080
Why....

239
00:18:08.330 --> 00:18:10.040
Why. thank you.

240
00:18:10.210 --> 00:18:11.880
Coming out of commercial.

241
00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:15.960
ln five. four. three. two....

242
00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:21.010
Welcome back. We're speaking
with Professor Donald Kessler.

243
00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:27.390
He's the chairman
of the American Academy of Astronautics.

244
00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:29.440
Professor...

245
00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:32.980
...isn't it weird that we sent
a space probe to Mars...

246
00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:34.730
...and we didn't even find anyone?

247
00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:38.280
Well. not really. Nathalie...

248
00:18:39.450 --> 00:18:41.530
...because we didn't get into the canals.

249
00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:43.570
The Martian canals are actually canyons.

250
00:18:44.030 --> 00:18:46.040
Some of them are over 100 miles deep.

251
